- Context: This page lists out different regulations to follow for creating a safe system of work. It also goes over some of the HSE guidance and best practices.
- Text: 0
Requires assessment and control of risks from hazardous substances
SSoW must incorporate appropriate control measures, exposure limits, and
monitoring requirements
Provision and Use of Work Equipment Regulations 1998 (PUWER)
•
Requires work equipment to be suitable, maintained, and used safely
SSOW must define safe use, inspection, and maintenance requirements
Lifting Operations and Lifting Equipment Regulations 1998 (LOLER)
0
Applies to lifting operations and equipment
Requires planning, supervision, and safe execution of lifting activities
Personal Protective Equipment at Work Regulations 1992 (as amended)
Requires provision and correct use of suitable PPE
SSoW must clearly define PPE requirements for specific tasks
Electricity at Work Regulations 1989
Requires systems to be constructed, maintained, and operated safely
SSoW must include controls for isolation, testing, and safe working practices
Dangerous Substances and Explosive Atmospheres Regulations 2002 (DSEAR)
Applies to flammable substances and explosive atmospheres
SSoW must address ignition control, zoning, and emergency arrangements
Pressure Systems Safety Regulations 2000 (PSSR)
•
Applies to pressure systems in industrial environments
Requires safe operation, maintenance, and written schemes of examination
HSE Guidance and Best Practice
In addition to statutory regulations, SSoW should align with relevant HSE Approved
Codes of Practice (ACOPs) and guidance documents, including:
•
•
HSG65: Managing for Health and Safety (Plan, Do, Check, Act model)
INDG163: Risk Assessment – A Brief Guide to Controlling Risks in the Workplace
HSG250: Guidance on Permit-to-Work Systems
